The  structural component is used to group multiple components together, to work around the restriction that a JSX expression can only evaluate to a single component. Since it's a virtual component, it doesn't correspond to anything in the DOM.

NOTE: This will soon be changed <> to match React 16.2's JSX syntax.

Here's an example that uses the  tag to insert multiple items into a list at once:
import { ObservableArray } from '@twist/core';

@Component
class Employee {
    @Attribute name;
    @Attribute bossName;

    render() {
        return 
            {this.name}
            {this.bossName}
        ;
    }
}

@Component
export default class MyComponent {

    employees = new ObservableArray([
        {name: 'Alice', bossName: 'Bob'},
        {name: 'Eve', bossName: 'NSA'}
    ]);

    render() {
        return 

        ;
    }
}

This avoids the need to wrap components in extra s, so it keeps the DOM cleaner.

NOTE: One thing to remember is that if you use  inside an tag, it's always interpreted as the SVG group element.

